© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce Griffin was born in 1446, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Harold William Griffin. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir Edward Deol Burton. She died in 1490, in her hometown, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1446–1490":"1446–1490","1457–1524":"1457–1524","1475–1543":"1475–1543","1480–1500":"1480–1500","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1524":"1524","1446":"1446","1457":"1457","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","Longnorlee, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dudley, Staffordshire, England":"Dudley, Staffordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1446–1490":"1446–1490","1457–1524":"1457–1524","1475–1543":"1475–1543","1480–1500":"1480–1500","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1524":"1524","1446":"1446","1457":"1457","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1480":"1480","1490":"149